|-
! Period
! Books
|-
| Pre-monarchic, prior to 11th century B.C.
|
* Mid 12th century B.C.: a section of the Book of Exodus, chapter 15 verses 1-21, the "[[Song of the Sea]]" and the Song of Miriam.{{sfn|Flynn|2008}}
* Other parts of the Bible which may date to the pre-Monarchic period are the Song of [[Deborah]], Judges 5:1-31; the [[Blessing of Moses]], Deuteronomy 33:1-29; and the [[Blessing of Jacob]], Genesis 49.<ref>http://www.usccb.org/bible/dt/33:29#05033029</ref>
|-
| Monarchic<br/>11th–7th centuries BCE<br/>c. 1050–586 BCE
|
* 11th-9th centuries B.C:  possibly the [[Yahwist]] portions of the Torah.  Possibly the [[book of Ruth]].
* Late 8th-early 7th: Possibly the [[book of Job]]; [[Book of Amos|Amos]] (initial composition of earliest layer);{{sfn|Radine|2010|p=71}} "[[Book of Isaiah|First Isaiah]]" (Isaiah 1–39),{{sfn|Brettler|2010|p=161–162}} [[Book of Hosea|Hosea]],{{sfn|Emmerson|2003|p=676}} [[Book of Micah|Micah]] (second half).{{sfn|Rogerson|2003a|p=690}}
* 7th: [[Book of Nahum|Nahum]] (based on its assumption of the fall of [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] and call for the destruction of [[Nineveh]]),{{sfn|O'Brien|2002|p=14}} [[Book of Zephaniah|Zephaniah]] (in the reign of [[Josiah]], c. 649–609 BCE),{{sfn|Gelston|2003|p=715}} [[Book of Habakkuk|Habakkuk]] (possibly shortly before the [[battle of Carchemish]], 605 BCE);{{sfn|Gelston|2003|p=710}} first edition of the [[Deuteronomistic history]] (books of [[Book of Joshua|Joshua]]/[[Book of Judges|Judges]]/[[Books of Samuel|Samuel]]/[[Books of Kings|Kings]]) in the reign of Josiah;{{sfn|Campbell|O'Brien|2000|p=2 and fn.6}} [[Deuteronomy]] 5–26 in the reign of Josiah.{{sfn|Rogerson|2003b|p=154}}<br>
|-
| Exilic<br/>6th century BCE<br/>586–539 BCE
|
* Core of [[Book of Obadiah|Obadiah]] around the fall of Jerusalem, 586 BCE.{{sfn|Gelston|2003|p=696}}
* Completion of [[Deuteronomistic history]] ([[Book of Joshua|Joshua]]/[[Book of Judges|Judges]]/[[Books of Samuel|Samuel]]/[[Books of Kings|Kings]]).{{sfn|Brettler|2007|p=311}}
* [[Deuteronomy]] expanded with addition of chapters 1–4 and 29–30 to serve as an introduction to the [[Deuteronomistic history]].{{sfn|Rogerson|2003b|p=154}}
* [[Book of Jeremiah|Jeremiah]] active in the last decade of the 7th century and first decades of the 6th;{{sfn|Biddle|2007|p=1073}}
* [[Book of Ezekiel|Ezekiel]] active in Babylon 592–571 BCE;{{sfn|Goldingay|2003|p=623}}
* "[[Book of Isaiah|Second Isaiah]]" (author of Isaiah 40–55) active in Babylon around mid-century.{{sfn|Blenkinsopp|2007|p=974}}
* Expansion and reshaping of [[Book of Hosea|Hosea]], [[Book of Amos|Amos]], [[Book of Micah|Micah]] and [[Book of Zephaniah|Zephaniah]].{{sfn|Carr|2011|p=342}}
* Possible early Psalms collection (psalms "of David") ending with psalm 89.{{sfn|Carr|2011|p=342}}
|-
| Post-exilic<br/>Persian<br/>5th–4th centuries BCE<br/>538–330 BCE
|
* [[Torah]] (books of [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]]/[[Book of Exodus|Exodus]]/[[Leviticus]]/[[Book of Numbers|Numbers]]), with 250 BCE as ''terminus ad quem'' (last possible date) for the production of the final text on the basis of the extant manuscript evidence.{{sfn|Greifenhagen|2003|p=212}}{{sfn|Enns|2012|p=5}}
* Deuteronomy revised with expansions to chapters 19–25 and addition of chapter 27 and 31–34 to serve as conclusion to the Torah.{{sfn|Rogerson|2003b|p=154}} 
* "[[Book of Isaiah|Third Isaiah]]" (Isaiah 56–66){{sfn|Blenkinsopp|2007|p=974}}
* Later version (the Masoretic Hebrew version) of [[Book of Jeremiah|Jeremiah]]{{sfn|Allen|2008|p=11}}
* [[Book of Haggai|Haggai]] (self-dated to the second year of the Persian king [[Darius I|Darius]] 520 BCE),{{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=214}}
* [[Book of Zechariah|Zechariah]] (chapters 1–8 contemporary with Haggai, chapters 9–14 from the 5th century){{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=214-215}}
* [[Book of Malachi|Malachi]] (5th century BCE, contemporaneous or immediately prior to the missions of Nehemiah and Ezra){{sfn|Carroll|2003|p=730}}
* [[Books of Chronicles|Chronicles]] (between 400–250 BC, probably in the period 350–300 BCE){{sfn|McKenzie|2004|p=32}}
* Origins of [[Ezra-Nehemiah]] (may have reached its final form as late as the Ptolemaic period, c. 300–200&nbsp;BCE).{{sfn|Grabbe|2003|p=00}}
|-
| Post-exilic<br/>Hellenistic<br/>3rd–2nd centuries BCE<br/>330–164 BCE
|
* [[Book of Job|Job]], [[Ecclesiastes]] and the [[Song of Songs]] (Could have been written in the 4th or even 5th centuries, but seem to reflect contact with Greek culture).{{sfn|Rogerson|2003c|p=8}}
* [[Book of Jonah]] (Persian or Hellenistic, no later than 2nd century BCE).{{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=217}}
* Most of the individual psalms making up the final third of the [[Book of Psalms]].{{sfn|Day|1990|p=16}}
|-
| Maccabean/Hasmonean<br/>2nd–1st centuries BCE<br/>164–4 BCE
|
* [[Book of Daniel|Daniel]] (164 BCE, combining newly-written visions, chapters 7–12, with the Persian and Hellenistic tales of chapters 1–6).{{sfn|Collins|2002|p=2}}
* [[1 Maccabees]]/[[2 Maccabees]]/[[3 Maccabees]]/possibly [[4 Maccabees]]; [[Book of Tobit|Tobit]], [[Book of Judith|Judith]], [[Additions to Daniel]] and [[Additions to Esther]]
* [[Wisdom of Solomon]] late 1st century BCE or early to mid 1st century CE.{{sfn|Rogerson|2003c|p=8}}
|-
| Roman<br/>1st century CE onward<br/>after 4 BCE
|
* [[4 Maccabees]] (after 63 BCE, probably mid-1st century CE).{{sfn|deSilva|2003|p=888}}
* [[Wisdom of Solomon]] (late 1st century BCE or early to mid 1st century CE).{{sfn|Rogerson|2003c|p=8}}
* New Testament (between c. 50–110 CE – see Table IV).
|}

==Table II: Hebrew Bible/Protestant Old Testament==

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Torah
! Date or range of dates most widely held by scholars
|-
|[[Book of Genesis]]<br>[[Book of Exodus]]<br>[[Book of Leviticus]]<br>[[Book of Numbers]]<br/>[[Book of Deuteronomy]]
|The majority of modern biblical scholars believe that the [[Torah]] – the books of Genesis, Exodus, Leviticus, Numbers and Deuteronomy – reached its present form in the [[Second Temple Judaism|post-Exilic period]].{{sfn|Enns|2012|p=5}} 

The five books are drawn from four "sources" (distinct schools of writers rather than individuals): the [[Priestly source]], the [[Yahwist]] and the [[Elohist]] (these two are often referred to collectively as the "non-Priestly" source), and the [[Deuteronomist]].{{sfn|Carr|2000|p=492}} There is general agreement that the Priestly source is post-exilic, but there is no agreement over the non-Priestly source(s).{{sfn|Carr|2000|p=492}}

* Genesis is a post-exilic work combining "Priestly" and "non-Priestly" material.{{sfn|Carr|2007|p=10}}
* Exodus is an anthology drawn from nearly all periods of Israel's history.{{sfn|Dozeman|2000|p=443}}
* Leviticus is entirely Priestly and dates from the exilic/post-exilic period.{{sfn|Houston|2003|p=102}}
* Numbers is a Priestly redaction (i.e., editing) of a [[Yahwist]]ic/non-Priestly original.{{sfn|McDermott|2002|p=21}}
* Deuteronomy, now the last book of the Torah, began as the set of religious laws (these make up the bulk of the book), was extended in the early part of the 6th century to serve as the introduction to the [[Deuteronomistic history]], and later still was detached from that history, extended yet again, and edited to conclude the Torah.{{sfn|Van Seters|2004|p=93}}
|-
! [[Nevi'im|Prophets]]
! Date or range of dates most widely held by scholars
|-
|Former Prophets: 
[[Book of Joshua#Composition|Book of Joshua]]<br>[[Book of Judges#Composition|Book of Judges]]<br>[[Books of Samuel#Composition|Books of Samuel]]<br>[[Books of Kings#Composition|Books of Kings]]
|This group of books, plus Deuteronomy, is called the "[[Deuteronomistic history]]" by scholars. The proposal that they made up a unified work was first advanced by [[Martin Noth]] in 1943, and has been widely accepted. Noth proposed that the entire history was the creation of a single individual working in the exilic period (6th century BCE); since then there has been wide recognition that the history appeared in two "editions", the first in the reign of Judah's [[King Josiah]] (late 7th century), the second during the exile (6th century).{{sfn|Campbell|O'Brien|2000|p=2 and fn.6}} Noth's dating was based on the assumption that the history was completed very soon after its last recorded event, the release of King [[Jehoiachin]] in Babylon c. 560 BCE; but some scholars have termed his reasoning inadequate, and the history may have been further extended in the post-exilic period.{{sfn|Person|2010|p=10-11}}
|-
|Three Major Prophets: 
[[Book of Isaiah#Composition|Book of Isaiah]]<br>[[Book of Jeremiah#Composition|Book of Jeremiah]]<br>[[Book of Ezekiel]]
|Scholars recognise three "sections" in the [[Book of Isaiah]]: Proto-Isaiah (the original 8th century Isaiah); Deutero-Isaiah (an anonymous prophet living in Babylon during the exile); and Trito-Isaiah (an anonymous author or authors in Jerusalem immediately after the exile).{{sfn|Sweeney|1998|p=76-77}}

The [[Book of Jeremiah]] exists in two versions, Greek (the version used in Orthodox Christian Bibles) and Hebrew (Jewish, Catholic and Protestant Bibles), with the Greek representing the earlier version.{{sfn|Allen|2008|p=7-8}} The Greek version was probably finalised in the early Persian period and translated into Greek in the 3rd century BCE, and the Hebrew version dates from some point between then and the 2nd century BCE.{{sfn|Sweeney|2010|p=94}}

The [[Book of Ezekiel]] describes itself as the words of the [[Ezekiel]] ben-Buzi, a priest living in exile in the city of [[Babylon]], and internal evidence dates the visions to between 593 and 571 BCE. While the book probably reflects much of the historic Ezekiel, it is the product of a long and complex history, with significant additions by a "school" of later followers.{{sfn|Blenkinsopp|1996|p=8}}{{sfn|Joyce|2009|p=16}}
|-
|[[Twelve Minor Prophets]]
|In the Hebrew Bible the [[Twelve Minor Prophets]] are a single collection edited in the [[Second Temple Judaism|Second Temple period]], but the collection is broken up in Christian Bibles.{{Sfn |Redditt|2003|pp=1–3, 9}} With the exception of [[Book of Jonah|Jonah]], which is a fictional work, there exists an original core of prophetic tradition behind each book:{{Sfn |Floyd|2000|p=9}}{{sfn|Dell|1996|pp=86–89}}
* [[Book of Hosea]]: second half of the 8th century BCE{{sfn|Emmerson|2003|p=676}}

* [[Book of Joel]]: late Persian or Hellenistic{{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=216}}
* [[Book of Amos]]: first half of the 8th century{{sfn|Carroll|2003|p=690}}
* [[Book of Obadiah]]: around the time of the fall of Jerusalem, 586 BCE{{sfn|Gelston|2003|p=696}}
* [[Book of Jonah]]: Persian or Hellenistic, no later than 2nd century BCE{{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=217}}
* [[Book of Micah]]: c. 750–700 BCE{{sfn|Rogerson|2003|p=690}}
* [[Book of Nahum]]: an "oracle concerning [[Nineveh]]", the [[Assyria]]n city destroyed in 612 BCE{{sfn|Rogerson|2003|p=708}}
* [[Book of Habakkuk]]: possibly shortly before the [[battle of Carchemish]], 605 BCE{{sfn|Gelston|2003|p=710}}
* [[Book of Zephaniah]]: reign of [[Josiah]]{{sfn|Gelston|2003|p=715}}
* [[Book of Haggai]]: self-dated to the second year of the Persian king [[Darius I|Darius]] (Darius the Great), 520 BCE{{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=214}}
* [[Book of Zechariah]]: first eight chapters contemporary with Haggai; chapters 9–14 from the 5th century{{sfn|Nelson|2014|p=214-215}}
* [[Book of Malachi]]: 5th century BCE, contemporaneous or immediately prior to the missions of Nehemiah and Ezra (which, however, are themselves difficult to date){{sfn|Carroll|2003|p=730}}
|-
![[Ketuvim|Writings]]
! Date or range of dates most widely held by scholars
|-
|[[Wisdom literature|Wisdom]] collection:<br/>[[Book of Job|Job]], [[Ecclesiastes]] and [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]]
|The books of [[Book of Job|Job]], [[Ecclesiastes]] and [[Book of Proverbs|Proverbs]] share a similar outlook which they themselves call "wisdom".{{sfn|Farmer|1998|p=129}} It is generally agreed that Job comes from between the 6th and 4th centuries BCE.{{sfn|Dell|2003|p=337}} Ecclesiastes can be no earlier than about 450 BCE, due to the presence of Persian loan-words and [[Aramaic]] idioms, and no later than 180 BCE, when the Jewish writer [[Ben Sira]] quotes from it.{{sfn|Seow|2007|p=944}}{{sfn|Fox|2004|p=xiv}} Proverbs is a "collection of collections" relating to a pattern of life which lasted for more than a millennium, and impossible to date.{{sfn|Clements|2003|p=438}}
|-
|Poetic works: [[Psalms]] and [[Book of Lamentations|Lamentations]]
|The psalms making up the first two-thirds of the [[book of Psalms|psalter]] are predominantly pre-exilic and the last third predominantly post-exilic.{{sfn|Day|1990|p=16}} The collected [[book of Psalms]] was possibly given its modern shape and division into five parts in the post-exilic period, although it continued to be revised and expanded well into Hellenistic and even Roman times.{{sfn|Coogan|Brettler|Newsom|2007|p=xxiii}} It is generally accepted that the destruction of Jerusalem by Babylon in 586&nbsp;BCE forms the background to the [[Book of Lamentations]].{{sfn|Hayes|1998|p=168}}
|-
|Histories: [[Books of Chronicles|Chronicles]] and [[Ezra-Nehemiah]]
|[[Books of Chronicles|Chronicles]] was composed between 400–250 BCE, probably in the period 350–300 BCE;{{sfn|McKenzie|2004|p=32}} [[Ezra-Nehemiah]] (two books in modern Bibles, but originally one) may have reached its final form as late as the Ptolemaic period, c. 300–200&nbsp;BCE.{{sfn|Grabbe|2003|p=00}}
|-
|Miscellaneous works: [[Book of Ruth]], [[Book of Esther]], [[Book of Daniel]], [[Song of Songs]]
|The [[Book of Ruth]] is commonly dated to the Persian period;{{sfn|Grabbe|2004|p=105}} [[Book of Esther|Esther]] to the 3rd or 4th centuries BCE; the [[Book of Daniel]] can be dated more precisely to 164 BCE thanks to its veiled prophecy of the death of a Greek king of Syria;{{sfn|Collins|1984|p=101}} and the [[Song of Songs]] could have been composed at any time after the 6th century BCE.{{sfn|Bloch|1995|p=23}}
|-
|}

==Table III: Deuterocanonical Old Testament==

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Book
! Date or range of dates most widely held by scholars
|-
| [[Book of Tobit|Tobit]]
| 225–175 BCE, on the basis of apparent use of language and references common to the post-exilic period, but lack of knowledge of the 2nd century BCE persecution of Jews.{{sfn|FitzMyer|2003|p=51}}
|-
| [[Book of Judith|Judith]]
| 150–100 BCE, although estimates range from the 5th century BCE to the 2nd century CE.{{sfn|West|2003|p=748}}
|-
| [[1 Maccabees]]
| 100 BCE{{sfn|Bartlett|2003|p=807}}
|-
| [[2 Maccabees]]
| c. 100 BCE{{sfn|Bartlett|2003|p=807}}
|-
| [[3 Maccabees]]
| 100–75 BCE "very probable"{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=866}}
|-
| [[4 Maccabees]]
| mid-1st century CE{{sfn|deSilva|2003|p=888}}
|-
| [[Book of Wisdom|Wisdom of Solomon]]
| late 1st century BCE/early 1st century CE, on the basis of shared outlook with other works dating from this time.{{sfn|Hayman|2003|p=763}}
|-
| [[Sirach]]
| 196–175 BCE, as the author implies that Simon the high priest had died (196 BCE), but shows no knowledge of the persecution of the Jews that began after 175 BCE.{{sfn|Snaith|2003|p=779}}
|-
| [[Additions to Daniel]]
| [[Prayer of Azariah]] (Song of the Three Holy Children); [[Bel and the Dragon]]: late 6th century;{{sfn|Harlow|2003|p=805}} [[Susanna and the Elders]]: possibly 95–80 BCE{{sfn|Spencer|2002|p=90}}
|-
| [[Book of Baruch|Baruch]] and [[Letter of Jeremiah]]
| 2nd century BCE, as Baruch uses Sirach (written c. 180 BCE) and is in turn used by the [[Psalms of Solomon]] (mid-1st century BCE). The Letter of Jeremiah, ch. 6:1–73 of the Book of Baruch, is sometimes considered a separate book.{{sfn|Schmitt|2003|p=799,802}}
|-
|}

==Table IV: New Testament==

{| class="wikitable sortable"
|-
! Book
! Date or range of dates most widely held by scholars
! Earliest&nbsp;known&nbsp;fragment
|-
| [[Gospel of Matthew]]
| 80–90 CE.{{sfn|Duling|2010|p=298-299}} This is based on three strands of evidence: (a) the setting of Matthew reflects the final separation of Church and Synagogue, about 85 CE; (b) it reflects the capture of Jerusalem and destruction of the Temple by the Romans in 70 CE; (c) it uses Mark, usually dated around 70 CE, as a source.{{sfn|France|2007|p=18}}
| {{Papyrus link|104}} (150–200 CE)
|-
| [[Gospel of Mark]]
| 65–73 CE.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=144-146}} References to persecution and to war in Judea suggest that its context was either [[Nero]]'s persecution of the Christians in Rome or the Jewish revolt.{{sfn|Perkins|1998|p=241}}
| {{Papyrus link|45}} (250 CE)
|-
| [[Gospel of Luke]]
| 80–90 CE.{{sfn|Charlesworth|2008|p=unpaginated}}{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=166}} Text indicates written a generation after that of the first disciples, uses Gospel of Mark, and appears to address concerns raised by the destruction of the Temple in 70 CE.{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=165}}
| {{Papyrus link|4}}, {{Papyrus link|75}} (175–250 CE)
|-
| [[Gospel of John]]
| 90–110 CE, the upper date based on textual evidence that the gospel was known in the early 2nd century, and the lower on an internal reference to the expulsion of Christians from the synagogues.{{sfn|Lincoln|2005|p=18}}
| {{Papyrus link|52}} (125–160 CE)
|-
| [[Acts of the Apostles|Acts]]
| 80-90 CE, on the grounds that Luke-Acts uses Mark as a source, looks back on the destruction of Jerusalem, and does not show any awareness of the letters of Paul (which began circulating late in the century); if, however, it does show awareness of the letters of Paul and also of the works of Josephus, then a date early in the 2nd century is more likely.{{sfn|Boring|2012|p=587}}{{sfn|Keener|2012|p=384}}{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=210}}
| {{Papyrus link|29}}, {{Papyrus link|45}}, {{Papyrus link|48}}, {{Papyrus link|53}}, {{Papyrus link|91}} (250 CE)
|-
| [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]]
| 57-58 CE.{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=275}} One of the indisputably genuine Pauline letters, written to the Romans as Paul was about to leave Asia Minor and Greece, and expressing his hopes to continue his work in Spain.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}} 
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[First Epistle to the Corinthians|1 Corinthians]]
| 53-57 CE.{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=295}} One of the indisputably genuine Pauline letters. Paul expresses his intention to re-visit the church he founded in the city c. 50–52 CE.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Second Epistle to the Corinthians|2 Corinthians]]
| 55-58 CE.{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=314}} One of the indisputably genuine Pauline letters.  Written by Paul in Macedonia after having left Ephesus.{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=313}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Epistle to the Galatians|Galatians]]
| c. 48 or 55 CE.{{sfn|Powell|2018|p=327}} One of the indisputably genuine Pauline letters.  The dating of this letter depends on whether it was written to the northern or southern portion of Galatia (with the former representing the later date). {{sfn|Powell|2018|p=326-327}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Ephesians]]
| c. 80–90 CE. The letter appears to have been written after Paul's death in Rome, by an author who uses his name.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Philippians]]
| c. 54–55 CE. A genuine Pauline letter, it mentions "Caesar's household," leading some scholars to believe that it is written from Rome, but some of the news in it could not have come from Rome. It seems rather to date from an earlier imprisonment, perhaps in Ephesus, from which Paul hopes to be released.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Colossians]]
| c. 62–70 CE. Some scholars believe Colossians dates from Paul's imprisonment in Ephesus around 55 CE, but differences in the theology suggest that it comes from much later in his career, around the time of his imprisonment in Rome.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[1 Thessalonians]]
| c. 51 CE. One of the earliest of the genuine Pauline epistles.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[2 Thessalonians]]
| c. 51 CE or post-70 CE. If this is a genuine Pauline epistle it follows closely on 1 Thessalonians. But some of the language and theology point to a much later date, from an unknown author using Paul's name.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|92}} (300 CE)
|-
| [[1 Timothy]], [[2 Timothy]], [[Epistle to Titus]]
| c. 100 CE. The two Timothy epistles and Titus reflect a much more developed Church organisation than that reflected in the genuine Pauline epistles.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| [[Codex Sinaiticus]] (350 CE){{Papyrus link|32}} (200 CE)
|-
| [[Paul's Letter to Philemon|Philemon]]
| c. 54–55 CE. A genuine Pauline epistle, written from an imprisonment (probably in Ephesus) that Paul expects will soon be over.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|87}} (3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Letter to the Hebrews|Hebrews]]
| c. 80–90 CE. The elegance of the Greek and the sophistication of the theology do not fit the genuine Pauline epistles, but the mention of Timothy in the conclusion led to its being included with the Pauline group from an early date.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Epistle of James|James]]
| c. 65–85 CE. Like Hebrews, James is not so much a letter as an exhortation; the style of the Greek makes it unlikely that it was actually written by James the brother of Jesus.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|20}}, {{Papyrus link|23}} (early 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[First Peter]]
| c. 75–90 CE{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|72}} (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Second Peter]]
| c. 110 CE. This is apparently the latest writing in the New Testament, quoting from Jude, assuming a knowledge of the Pauline letters, and including a reference to the gospel story of the [[Transfiguration of Christ]].{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|72}} (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Epistles of John]]
| 90–110 CE.{{sfn|Kim|2003|p=250}} The letters give no clear indication, but scholars tend to place them about a decade after the Gospel of John.{{sfn|Kim|2003|p=250}}
| {{Papyrus link|9}}, [[Uncial 0232]], [[Codex Sinaiticus]] (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Epistle of Jude|Jude]]
| Uncertain. The references to "brother of James" and to "what the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ foretold" suggest that it was written after the apostolic letters were in circulation, but before 2 Peter, which uses it.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|72}} (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]]
| c. 95 CE. The date is suggested by clues in the visions pointing to the reign of the emperor [[Domitian]].{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|98}} (150–200 CE)
|}

