'''WinOps''' (a [[portmanteau]] of "[[Windows]]" and "[[DevOps]]") is a term used referring to the cultural movement of DevOps practices for a Microsoft-centric view.<ref>{{Citation | last = Weinberger | first = Matt | title = Microsoft study finds everybody wants DevOps but Culture is a Challenge | publisher = Computerworld | date = 25 November 2014 | url = http://www.computerworld.com/article/2851974/microsoft-study-finds-everybody-wants-devops-but-culture-is-a-challenge.html }}</ref> It emphasizes the use of the [[Cloud computing|cloud]], [[automation]] and integrating development and [[ Information technology operations|IT operations]] into one fluid method on the Windows platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.v3.co.uk/v3-uk/news/2460007/microsoft-announces-open-source-blockchain-based-identity-platform-for-azure|title=Microsoft announces open source blockchain-based identity platform for Azure| website=v3.co.uk|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>
== Etymology == The term 'WinOps' was coined at the [[London]] DevOps meetup held at [[Facebook]] in June 2015. As an amalgamation of Windows and DevOps, it represents the new emphasis on using existing DevOps methodologies in the traditionally less open-source Microsoft space.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@Prism_Digital/prism-digital-s-world-first-conference-61be015baf2a#.wvzw2c7lj|title=Prism Digital's world first conference|last=Digital|first=Prism|date=2015-10-16|website=Medium|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sammart.in/winops-conference-london-2/|title=WinOps Conference London #2|date=2016-05-26|website=Sam Martin|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>
== Community == Since the first WinOps conference in September 2015, there have been multiple meetups and a second conference which was held in May 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://skeltonthatcher.com/blog/winops-conf-2016-devops-ification-of-windows-server/|title=WinOps Conf 2016 - DevOps-ification of Windows Server - Skelton Thatcher Consulting|date=2016-05-28|website=Skelton Thatcher Consulting|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@Prism_Digital/winops-conf-1b845b6a7296#.mlvpjobjp|title=WinOps Conf|last=Digital|first=Prism|date=2016-06-01|website=Medium|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref> The WinOps meetup group has an active community with over 1,000 members. Their motto is "Windows in a DevOps World". They focus on shared experiences using Windows centred products and tools for establishing DevOps goals.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Winops Meetup london |url= https://www.meetup.com/WinOps/ |website= meetup |access-date= 16 February 2017 }} </ref> [[File:WinOps logo.png|thumb]] {| class="wikitable" !Date !Type !Host !Speakers |- |[http://www.meetup.com/WinOps/events/224736510/ 22 September 2015] |Conference |The Brewery | |- |[http://www.meetup.com/WinOps/events/226051235/ 17 November 2015] |Meetup |JustEat |Peter Mounce - JustEat |- |[http://www.meetup.com/WinOps/events/227313132/ 16 January 2016] |Meetup |HP Enterprise |Arne Luhrs - HPE IT Andy Burgin - Sky Betting and Gaming |- |[http://www.meetup.com/WinOps/events/228703443/ 23 February 2016] |Meetup |Wonga.com |Ryan Yates Ricard Clau - Wonga.com |- |[http://www.meetup.com/WinOps/events/228704653/ 22 March 2016] |Meetup |Microsoft |Marcus Robinson - Microsoft Nicolas Corrarello - Puppet |- |[http://www.meetup.com/WinOps/events/229065341/ 20 April 2016] |Meetup |HP Enterprise |Ben Hall - Ocelot Uproar Steve Thair - DevOpsGuys |- |[http://winops.org/ 24-25 May 2016] |Conference |CodeNode - Skills Matter |[[Jeffrey Snover]] - Microsoft Ed Wilson - Microsoft Michael Greene - Microsoft |- |[http://www.cvent.com/events/winops-conf-2017/event-summary-f659578b8953404c8c3d3d289a89589b.aspx 20-21 September 2017] |Conference |CodeNode - Skills Matter |Jeffrey Snover - Microsoft Sam Guckenheimer - Microsoft
|}
== The Linux challenge == Windows and [[Linux]] are very different; not just technologically, but philosophically. Tools are a major component to establishing DevOps, and the lack of Windows-centric tools limited early Windows DevOps adoptions as most initial supporting technologies emerged from Linux and [[open-source]] communities.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eagles |first=Harry |title=DevOps Technology in a Windows World |url= https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/uktechnet/2016/05/24/devops-technology-in-a-windows-world/ |website= Microsoft TechNet |date=24 May 2016 }} </ref> WinOps boils down to addressing the same challenges as DevOps, using different tools.<ref>{{Citation | last = Thair | first= Steve | title = DevOps for Windows "In the Wild" | series = DevOps Exchange London | place = London | date= 24 March 2015 }} </ref>
